Choice DRT Participant Summaries

20 participants responded to either the high (1), low (2), or both (3) intensities of light presented by the DRT. When responding to the high or low light, that intensity of light appeared 100% of the time. This is referred to as mode . Participants also either counted backwards by 3s from a number produced by a random number generator between 100 and 1000 (1), or they did not (0). This is referred to as load .

# READ DATA ------------------------

fulldata<-read.csv("output2raw.csv", header=TRUE)


cleandata <- subset(fulldata, rt > 200 & rt < 5000 & mode != 0)

cleandata$subid <- factor(cleandata$subid)
cleandata$load <- factor(cleandata$load)
cleandata$mode <- factor(cleandata$mode)
cleandata$rt <- as.integer(cleandata$rt)


require(plyr)
cleandata$response <- revalue(cleandata$response, c("wrong"=0, "correct"=1))

cleandata$response <- droplevels(cleandata$response)
cleandata$mode <- droplevels(cleandata$mode)

cleandata$response <- as.numeric(levels(cleandata$response))[cleandata$response]

clean.mean <- aggregate(list(cleandata$rt,cleandata$response),
                        by = list(as.factor(cleandata$mode),as.factor(cleandata$load),
                                  as.factor(cleandata$stimulus),cleandata$subid),
                        FUN = 'mean')

colnames(clean.mean) <- c("mode","load","stimulus","subid","rt","acc")

clean.mean$acc <- ((clean.mean$acc)*100)

Full data and cleaned data comparisons

full_counts <- ftable(1~subid+mode+load, data=fulldata)
clean_counts <- ftable(1~subid+mode+load, data=cleandata)

Mean number of trials per block for the full dataset compared to the cleaned dataset (RTs greater than 200 and less than 5000). There are 6 blocks with 3 DRT modes and 2 load levels. There are 2 blocks with just steering at the 2 load levels.

mean(full_counts)
## [1] 190.55
mean(clean_counts)
## [1] 189.5917

Response Bias

Mean response accuracy for choice task (3) blocks by high (1) and low (2) DRT light stimulus intensities

require(doBy)
stimcheck <- subset(cleandata, mode == 3)
summaryBy(response~load + mode + stimulus, data=stimcheck,FUN=c(mean,median,var), na.rm=TRUE)
##   load mode stimulus response.mean response.median response.var
## 1    0    3        1     0.7446184               1    0.1902549
## 2    0    3        2     0.7383838               1    0.1932708
## 3    1    3        1     0.6929735               1    0.2128696
## 4    1    3        2     0.7052298               1    0.2079906

It looks as if on average there is no meaningful response bias between the high (1) and low (2) DRT light stimulus intensities

Individually though, there are some response biases.

For each participant, I calculated a difference score from their percent accuracy (response.diff) to the choice task (3) broken down by the difference between their accuracy to the high (1) and low (2) lights.

stimcheck <- subset(cleandata, mode == 3)
bias <- summaryBy(response~ mode + subid + load + stimulus, data=stimcheck,FUN=c(mean,var), na.rm=TRUE)

bigbias <- ddply(bias, .(subid), transform, response.mean=(response.mean[stimulus == 1]-response.mean[stimulus == 2])*100)

colnames(bigbias) <- c("mode","subid","stimulus","load","response.diff","response.var")


myvars <- c("subid","load","response.diff")
bigbias <- bigbias[myvars]

bigbias <- unique(bigbias)

dev <- ggplot(data=bigbias,aes(x=as.factor(subid), y = response.diff, fill = as.factor(load))) +
  geom_bar(data = bigbias,
           stat = "identity") + scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(-50,0,50),labels = abs(seq(-50,0,50))) +
  coord_flip() + theme_light()
dev

Its nice to see that one light intensity was not consistently preferred between participants, but it did seem to be consistently preferred within participants.

Plots of Means

Reaction Time

This plot shows the expected pattern for RTs of high (1) and low (2) lights, as well as the choice (3) RTs, and the slower counting (1) compared to not counting (0) conditions. 
qplot(mode, rt, data=clean.mean, geom="boxplot", color = load, ylim = c(0,1500)) +
  theme_light() + ggtitle("Reaction Time by \n high (1) low (2) and choice (3) \n light intensities")

#Look at RT's by condition

Accuracy

This plot shows the expected accuracy pattern for high (1) and low (2) lights, as well as the choice (3) task. There may be a more subtle effect of counting. 

qplot(mode, acc, data=clean.mean, geom="boxplot",color = load, ylim = c(40,120)) +
  theme_light() + ggtitle("Accuracy by \n high (1) low (2) and choice (3) \n light intensities")

cleandata3 <- subset(clean.mean, mode == 3)

Summaries of RT and accuracy by stimulus and load

dfrt <- summaryBy(rt~ as.factor(stimulus) + as.fator(load), data=stimcheck)
dfacc<- summaryBy(acc~ as.factor(stimulus) + as.fator(load), data=cleandata3)

ggplot(dfrt, aes(x = as.factor(stimulus), y=rt.mean, colour = load)) + 
  geom_point(size=5) + ylim(800,1300) +
  geom_segment(aes(x=stimulus[1],y=rt.mean[1], xend=stimulus[3],yend=rt.mean[3]), color="red",data=dfrt) +
  geom_segment(aes(x=stimulus[2],y=rt.mean[2], xend=stimulus[4],yend=rt.mean[4]), color="light blue",data=dfrt)

ggplot(dfacc,aes(x = as.factor(stimulus), y=acc.mean, colour = load)) + 
  geom_point(size=5) + ylim (60,90) + 
  geom_segment(aes(x=stimulus[1],y=acc.mean[1], xend=stimulus[3],yend=acc.mean[3]), color="red",data=dfacc) +
  geom_segment(aes(x=stimulus[2],y=acc.mean[2], xend=stimulus[4],yend=acc.mean[4]), color="light blue",data=dfacc)

Cumulative Distribution Functions

p <- ggplot(cleandata, aes(rt, colour = as.factor(stimulus), linetype = load)) + 
  stat_ecdf() + theme_light()
p + facet_wrap(~mode,ncol = 3, labeller = labeller(mode = label_both, load = label_both)) + 
  ggtitle("Cumulative Distribution Function \n by Load and Mode")

p + facet_wrap(~subid, labeller = labeller(subid = label_both)) + theme_light() + 
  ggtitle("Cumulative Distribution Function \n by Subject, Load and Mode")
